

USER MANAGEMENT RUNBOOK
========================

Purpose: Step-by-step procedures for managing users in FreeIPA (centralized authentication system).

==== Overview ====

FreeIPA provides centralized user management for all homelab VMs. Users created in FreeIPA automatically have access to all domain-joined systems.

User Roles:
- SuperAdmin - Infrastructure owners (full access)
- Admin - IT operations staff (elevated access)
- Developer - Technical users (limited access)
- User - Non-technical staff (basic access)

Automation:
All user management operations are automated via Ansible playbooks located at: /opt/ansible/playbooks/

==== Prerequisites ====

Before running user management playbooks:
- SSH access to mgmt.lab.local
- FreeIPA admin credentials
- Ansible installed on mgmt.lab.local

==== Add New User (Single) ====

Purpose: Create a new user account with access to homelab VMs

Procedure:

1. SSH to management server:
ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local

2. Navigate to playbooks directory:
cd /opt/ansible/playbooks

3. Run onboarding playbook:
ansible-playbook onboard-user.yml

4. Answer prompts:
- Username: (lowercase, no spaces, 3-32 characters)
- First Name: (user's first name)
- Last Name: (user's last name)
- Email Address: (valid email format)
- Role: superadmin/admin/developer/user

5. Verify user created:
ipa user-show [username]

6. Verify group membership:
ipa group-show [role]s

7. Test user access:
ssh [username]@apps.lab.local
# User will be prompted to set password on first login

8. Test sudo access (if admin/developer/superadmin):
ssh [username]@apps.lab.local 'sudo whoami'
# Should return: root (without password prompt)

Example:
ansible-playbook onboard-user.yml
Username: jdoe
First Name: John
Last Name: Doe
Email Address: jdoe@lab.local
Role: developer

Notes:
- User account is automatically available on all FreeIPA-joined VMs
- Default shell is /bin/bash
- Home directory created automatically on first login
- Password must be changed on first login
- User creation logged to: /opt/ansible/logs/user-onboarding.log

==== Add Multiple Users (Batch) ====

Purpose: Create multiple user accounts at once from a YAML file

Procedure:

1. SSH to management server:
ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local

2. Create users definition file:
nano /opt/ansible/vars/new-users.yml

3. Add users in YAML format:
users:

    username: jdoe

first_name: John

  last_name: Doe\\
  email: jdoe@lab.local\\
  role: developer\\
\\
- username: asmith\\
  first_name: Alice\\
  last_name: Smith\\
  email: asmith@lab.local\\
  role: admin\\


Save and exit

4. Run batch onboarding playbook:
cd /opt/ansible/playbooks
ansible-playbook onboard-users-batch.yml

5. Confirm file path when prompted:
Path to users YAML file: /opt/ansible/vars/new-users.yml

6. Review output:
- Playbook shows which users will be created
- Skips users that already exist
- Displays summary of created users

7. Verify users created:
ipa user-find

8. Notify users of their new accounts

Notes:
- Existing users are skipped automatically (no errors)
- All users logged to: /opt/ansible/logs/user-onboarding.log
- Users can be added incrementally to the same YAML file

==== Modify User ====

Purpose: Change user attributes (role, email, name) or reset password

Procedure:

1. SSH to management server:
ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local

2. Run modify playbook:
cd /opt/ansible/playbooks
ansible-playbook modify-user.yml

3. Answer prompts:
- Username to modify: [username]
- Action: change_role/change_email/change_name/reset_password
- New value: (depends on action)

4. Verify change:
ipa user-show [username]

Action-Specific Details:

Change Role:
- Action: change_role
- New value: superadmin/admin/developer/user
- Example: Promote jdoe from developer to admin

    Username: jdoe
    Action: change_role
    New value: admin


Change Email:
- Action: change_email
- New value: new.email@lab.local
- Example: Update email address

    Username: jdoe
    Action: change_email
    New value: john.doe@lab.local


Change Name:
- Action: change_name
- New value: FirstName LastName (with space)
- Example: User changed their name

    Username: jdoe
    Action: change_name
    New value: Jonathan Doe


Reset Password:
- Action: reset_password
- New value: (leave blank, press Enter)
- User will be forced to set new password on next login
- Example: User forgot password

    Username: jdoe
    Action: reset_password
    New value: (press Enter)


Notes:
- All modifications logged to: /opt/ansible/logs/user-modifications.log
- Role changes take effect immediately
- User must log out and back in for group changes to apply

==== Remove User (Offboard) ====

Purpose: Disable or delete user accounts

Procedure:

1. SSH to management server:
ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local

2. Run offboarding playbook:
cd /opt/ansible/playbooks
ansible-playbook offboard-user.yml

3. Answer prompts:
- Username to offboard: [username]
- Action: disable/delete

4. Review user details displayed

5. Confirm action:
Type 'yes' to confirm, or 'no' to cancel

6. Verify user removed:
ipa user-show [username]
# Should fail if deleted, show “disabled” if disabled

Disable vs Delete:

Disable (Recommended):
- User account preserved
- User cannot log in
- Data and settings retained
- Can be re-enabled later: ipa user-enable [username]
- Use for: temporary removal, departing contractors, leave of absence

Delete (Permanent):
- User account permanently removed
- Cannot be undone
- User details backed up to: /opt/ansible/logs/deleted-users/[username]-[date].txt
- Use for: permanent termination, security incidents

Example (Disable):
ansible-playbook offboard-user.yml
Username to offboard: jdoe
Action: disable
[Review details]
Confirm: yes

Example (Delete):
ansible-playbook offboard-user.yml
Username to offboard: jdoe
Action: delete
[Review details]
Confirm: yes

Notes:
- All offboarding logged to: /opt/ansible/logs/user-offboarding.log
- Deleted user details backed up for audit purposes
- User home directories remain on VMs (manual cleanup if needed)

==== Re-enable Disabled User ====

Purpose: Restore access for a previously disabled user

Procedure:

1. SSH to FreeIPA server:
ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local

2. Authenticate as admin:
kinit admin

3. Re-enable user account:
ipa user-enable [username]

4. Verify user enabled:
ipa user-show [username]
# Should not show “disabled”

5. Test user access:
ssh [username]@apps.lab.local

Notes:
- User retains all previous group memberships
- User retains previous password
- User can log in immediately

==== User Roles and Permissions ====

SuperAdmin (Tier 0):
- Group: superadmins
- Members: jireland
- Sudo: Full (all commands, all hosts, no password)
- SSH Access: All VMs (mgmt, apps, mntr)
- Purpose: Infrastructure owners with complete control
- Use case: Primary homelab administrator

Admin (Tier 1):
- Group: it_admins
- Members: [IT operations staff]
- Sudo: Limited (systemctl, docker, journalctl, reboot, apt/yum, docker-compose)
- SSH Access: All VMs (mgmt, apps, mntr)
- Purpose: Day-to-day operations and user management
- Use case: Secondary administrators, trusted IT staff

Developer (Tier 2):
- Group: developers
- Members: [Technical users]
- Sudo: Very limited (docker logs, systemctl restart - apps VM only)
- SSH Access: apps.lab.local only
- Purpose: Technical users with minimal elevated access
- Use case: Developers needing to deploy/debug applications

User (Tier 3):
- Group: users
- Members: All users by default
- Sudo: None
- SSH Access: None (unless specific HBAC rule created)
- Purpose: Non-technical staff, read-only access
- Use case: HR, finance, general staff accessing web services only

==== Manual User Operations ====

For operations not covered by playbooks, use FreeIPA CLI directly:

Authenticate to FreeIPA:
ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local
kinit admin
# Enter admin password

List all users:
ipa user-find

Show user details:
ipa user-show [username]

List all groups:
ipa group-find

Show group members:
ipa group-show [groupname]

Add user to group manually:
ipa group-add-member [groupname] –users=[username]

Remove user from group manually:
ipa group-remove-member [groupname] –users=[username]

Change user shell:
ipa user-mod [username] –shell=/bin/zsh

Lock user account (alternative to disable):
ipa user-disable [username]

Unlock user account:
ipa user-enable [username]

View sudo rules:
ipa sudorule-find

Show sudo rule details:
ipa sudorule-show [rulename]

==== Troubleshooting ====

User cannot log in:

Diagnosis:
ipa user-show [username]
# Check if account is disabled

ssh [username]@apps.lab.local
# Check error message

Solution:
# If disabled:
ipa user-enable [username]

# If password expired:
ipa passwd [username]
# User sets new password on next login

# If HBAC blocking (if configured):
ipa hbacrule-add-user [rule] –users=[username]

Sudo not working:

Diagnosis:
ssh [username]@apps.lab.local
sudo -l
# Shows which commands user can run

ipa sudorule-show [role]_sudo
# Verify user's role group is included

Solution:
# Verify user in correct group:
ipa group-show [role]s

# If missing, add user to group:
ipa group-add-member [role]s –users=[username]

# User must log out and back in:
exit
ssh [username]@apps.lab.local
sudo whoami # Should work now

User exists error when onboarding:

Diagnosis:
ipa user-show [username]
# Confirms user already exists

Solution:
# Either:
# 1. Use different username
# 2. Delete existing user first (if appropriate):
ansible-playbook offboard-user.yml

# 3. Or modify existing user instead:
ansible-playbook modify-user.yml

Playbook fails with “kinit” error:

Diagnosis:
kinit admin
# Try authenticating manually

Solution:
# If credentials expired:
kinit admin
# Enter password

# Then re-run playbook

User can't access specific VM:

Diagnosis:
# Check HBAC rules (if configured):
ipa hbacrule-find

Solution:
# If HBAC enabled, add user to appropriate rule:
ipa hbacrule-add-user [rule] –users=[username]

# Or add user's group:
ipa hbacrule-add-user [rule] –groups=[groupname]

==== Logs and Audit Trail ====

All user management operations are logged:

Onboarding log:
/opt/ansible/logs/user-onboarding.log
Format: timestamp | CREATED | username | role | name | email | by [admin]

Modifications log:
/opt/ansible/logs/user-modifications.log
Format: timestamp | ACTION | username | new_value | by [admin]

Offboarding log:
/opt/ansible/logs/user-offboarding.log
Format: timestamp | DISABLE/DELETE | username | by [admin]

Deleted user backups:
/opt/ansible/logs/deleted-users/[username]-[timestamp].txt
Contains full user details before deletion

View recent user changes:
tail -20 /opt/ansible/logs/user-onboarding.log
tail -20 /opt/ansible/logs/user-modifications.log
tail -20 /opt/ansible/logs/user-offboarding.log

==== Best Practices ====

Security:
- Always use disable instead of delete unless absolutely necessary
- Review sudo access regularly
- Audit user accounts quarterly
- Use strong, unique passwords
- Enable 2FA for superadmin accounts (future)

Operations:
- Test new user accounts after creation
- Document reason for role changes
- Notify users before disabling accounts
- Backup user data before deletion
- Keep audit logs for compliance

Automation:
- Use batch onboarding for multiple users
- Prefer playbooks over manual CLI commands
- Version control user definition files
- Review playbook logs after execution

